re, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1045–1095":"about 1045–1095","1045–1095":"1045–1095","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1049–Female":"1049–Deceased","1074–1130":"1074–1130","1018–1110":"1018–1110","1021–Female":"1021–Deceased","1066":"1066","1110":"1110","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1074":"1074","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1018":"1018","1049":"1049","1101":"1101","1045":"1045","about 1045":"about 1045","Wormegay, Norfolk, England":"Wormegay, Norfolk, England","Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Fitzwilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":21,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":41,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Fitzwilliam de Wormegay was born about 1045, in Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure, Normandy, France, his father, Hermer de Wormegay, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Hermer de Wormegay, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Richard Fitzwilliam de Wormegay. He died in 1095, in Wormegay, Norfolk, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1045–1095":"umbes 1045–1095","1045–1095":"1045–1095","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1049–Female":"1049–Surnud","1074–1130":"1074–1130","1018–1110":"1018–1110","1021–Female":"1021–Surnud","1066":"1066","1110":"1110","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1074":"1074","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1018":"1018","1049":"1049","1101":"1101","1045":"1045","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Wormegay, Norfolk, England":"Wormegay, Norfolk, England","Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1045–1095":"noin 1045–1095","1045–1095":"1045–1095","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1049–Female":"1049–Kuollut","1074–1130":"1074–1130","1018–1110":"1018–1110","1021–Female":"1021–Kuollut","1066":"1066","1110":"1110","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1074":"1074","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1018":"1018","1049":"1049","1101":"1101","1045":"1045","about 1045":"noin 1045","Wormegay, Norfolk, England":"Wormegay,